git revert (Simple Explanation)

git revert is used to undo a commit, but without deleting the commit history.

Instead, Git creates a new commit that reverses the changes made by a previous commit.

Simple Idea

Suppose you added a wrong change.

Commit history:

Commit1 → Commit2 → Commit3

If Commit3 is wrong, run:

git revert <commit-id>

Git will create a new commit that cancels Commit3 changes.
